{
  "text": "The results obtained in the present study when a 5-HT 1A receptor agonist was combined with fluoxetine provided further support for the idea that postsynaptic 5-HT 1A receptor activity is involved in the control of impulsive behavior. The onset of activity (number of trials to significantly increase delay to the larger reward) was sooner after administration of a 5-HT 1A receptor agonist (8-OH-DPAT) in addition to fluoxetine than when fluoxetine had been administered by itself. Possibly, the addition of a 5-HT 1A receptor agonist amplified the de-sensitization of the 5-HT 1A presynaptic receptor and more quickly normalized 5-HT neuronal firing. Thus, as well as increased overall 5-HT neurotransmission, the activity of the postsynaptic 5-HT 1A receptor also would be enhanced. 5-HT 1A receptor partial agonists, such as buspirone, have been demonstrated to augment the antidepressant effect of SSRIs in a clinical setting [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "21330292"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "21330292": {
      "title": "Buspirone augmentation of antidepressant therapy",
      "abstract": "Thirty outpatients meeting DSM-III-R or DSM-IV criteria for major depression, single or recurrent episode, and failing to respond to an adequate trial of an antidepressant (>6 weeks at recommended dosage) received buspirone (20-30 mg/day) for 4 or 5 weeks in addition to their existing antidepressant"
    }
  }
}